    "notes": "Week 7 Day 5 of Talk 5 (Week 1 of 1, Single-Week Talk). Psychology & Bias focus: Psychological barriers preventing multidisciplinary thinking. Core frameworks: Man-with-a-Hammer Tendency (reliance on familiar models), Incentive-Caused Bias in Education (institutional resistance to reform), Use-It-or-Lose-It Tendency (skills atrophy without practice), Availability Tendency (defaulting to available models from own discipline), Twaddle Tendency (accepting nonsense from narrow specialists). 5 case snapshots - LTCM collapse (unidisciplinary finance failure), Quibi's $1.75B failure (Hollywood + tech thinking ignored psychology/economics/sociology), Product manager optimized only metrics (psychology/economics ignored), Berkshire's See's Candies (multidisciplinary success), Founder ignored incentive alignment (psychology atrophy). 5 actionable takeaways including audit of 3 recent decisions for disciplinary dominance, discipline checklist before major decisions, unidisciplinary disaster inversion scenarios, daily simulator routine, skepticism of single-discipline expert confidence. Mental model drill on Man-with-a-Hammer + Use-It-or-Lose-It with 5 prompts for bias recognition. 3 reflection questions on self-audit, environment/culture incentives, latticework building across disciplines. Personal commitment: Conduct man-with-a-hammer audit on most important recent decision identifying disciplinary dominance and 2 alternative perspectives (15-20 min). Talk 5 Day 5 complete. Next: Day 6 Case Study focus. Message delivered successfully."
